aras fid="td"><Para>Barcelona, Spain</Para><Para>''It's quite a cultural mix,'' says Astrid Schweitzer, 22, of Die Motte, the Barcelona-based jewelry label that she runs with her co-designer Anel Rinat, 27. Schweitzer, who is of Chilean, Peruvian and German descent, was raised in Barcelona's vibrant Poble Sec neighborhood, which overlooks the Mediterranean. Rinat is Kazakh, and grew up in Almaty, surrounded by the sagebrush steppe and snow-capped mountains of Central Asia; she was shaped by the city's Scythian and Soviet heritage. The two met in a jewelry arts school in Barcelona in 2016 and quickly became friends. ''We connected by intuition,'' Schweitzer says.</Para><Para>The brand is an amalgamation of their distinct backgrounds, and the pair produces precious-metal wire pieces that are both delicate and evocative: gilded dove-shaped barrettes that recall Picasso's 1961 drawing ''La Colombe Bleue,'' rings made from miniature handmade silver links and face-shaped hoop earrings with dangling chains that look like tears. The designers' process is instinctual, like their friendship: Ideas for new projects are formed during meandering walks through the foggy forests of Montseny or in their airy studio near PlaÃ§a d'Espanya, where they manipulate metals and sculpt. ''It's like meditating,'' Rinat says. Their most recent collection comprises wisp-like earrings, brooches and rings inspired by the Swiss artist Alberto Giacometti. ''We try to pull from our contrast and create a balance,'' Schweitzer says.</Para><Para>______</Para><Para>Juliette LaloÃ«</Para><Para>Designer: Juliette Avignon</Para><Para>Paris, France</Para><Para>In the summer of 2011, on the day before her 20th birthday, the French jewelry designer Juliette Avignon dozed off while driving her scooter and careened into a tree. She woke up in the hospital with a broken jaw and femur, and was only consoled by a book of Frida Kahlo's writings. Like the Mexican painter, who took up art after a bus accident, Avignon started ''tinkering with accessories'' while she was bedridden. ''After six months, I could walk again,'' she says, ''and I have not stopped making jewelry since.''</Para><Para>Today, her namesake brand, Juliette LaloÃ« (LaloÃ« is her mother's last name), features a range of simple yet striking designs, from hoop earrings fashioned after Greek pottery to eye-shaped earrings that recall the line drawings of the French writer Jean Cocteau. ''It's not just jewelry,'' says the self-taught designer, who splits her time between Paris and Provence. ''My work tells a story.'' Her latest collection depicts a port town in Normandy, and includes gold drop earrings that look like puddles, wavy oversize hoops dotted with textural wild-oyster pearls and bangles that resemble frothy sea foam. She makes each piece by hand, shaping it in brass, before sending it to a ProvenÃ§al artisan to be gilded. ''I like the antique and imperfect appearance,'' Avignon says.</Para><Para>______</Para><Para>Noon</Para><Para>Designer: Sophia Armstrong</Para><Para>Vancouver, Canada</Para><Para>The jewelry designer Sophia Armstrong, 26, begins each of her undulating one-of-a-kind pieces by making her own silver, a labor-intensive process that she nevertheless describes as ''incredibly soothing.'' Then, she experiments with shape. The sculptors Barbara Hepworth and Isamu Noguchi are consistent influences for her fluid silver forms, she says, as is the Joan MirÃ³ painting ''Woman dreaming of escape.'' ''It has a childish playfulness to it that reminds me to trust my instincts when I'm designing,'' explains Armstrong, who studied jewelry art and design at Vancouver Community College.</Para><Para>But the designer's biggest influence remains her late grandmother, a painter and photographer who would collect jewelry during her travels in Mexico. As a child, Armstrong would dress up in her glimmering silver pieces, including turquoise-inlaid rings and a bola necklace -- a spherical pendant with a soft chime that expectant mothers sometimes wear. ''When she passed, I inherited her entire collection,'' she says. ''The sound of that chime still reminds me of her.'' The pieces Armstrong now creates for Noon, the jewelry line she founded in 2015, are just as harmonious -- an artful balance of hard and soft. Rose-pink pearls dangle from amorphous silver studs, and starkly architectural chokers and rings are flecked with iridescent freshwater pearls. ''I have always been interested in portraying unusual beauty in my work,'' says Armstrong.</Para><Para>This is a more complete version of the story than the one that appeared in print.</Para></TailParas><Byline fid="by" index="field">By ZIO BARITAUX </Byline><Credit fid="cr" index="field"></Credit><Contact fid="ct" index="field"></Contact><Notes fid="rf" index="field"></Notes><Art fid="art" index="field">(PHOTOGRAPH BY BAURZHAN BISMILDIN, COURTESY OF DIE MOTTE) </Art><Copyright fid="cy" index="field">Copyright 2018 The New York Times Company.  All Rights Reserved. </Copyright></Article></ArchiveDoc><AdocTOC adoctype="article"><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/ArchiveDoc::Article" type="arttext"></Item><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/InvertText" type="invtext"></Item></AdocTOC></DistDoc>

